Inference

After applying AIC, BIC, cross-validation(5, 10), bootstrap the results are somewhat differenct. AIC tells us that the best model to choose is with 7 predictors, BIC tells us that the model with 3 predictors the best. Both cross validation agree with the result of AIC, i.e.the model with 7 predictors is the best. So does bootstrap. The only metric supporting BICs conclusion is the test error, as it is the least for a model with size 3. But test error should not be relied upon as it can be a case of an unfortunate split. We also have a better measure of how each of our subset-feature models perform, which is the 10 fold and 5 fold cross validation.

As there is a greater support in favor of a model with 7 subsets, I would select that over a model with size 3.
